<content>
    <section id="idm512615366528">
      <title>The Existence of the z-Transform</title>
      <para id="idm512615365968">Recall the definition of the z-transform for some discrete-time infinite length signal <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">x[n]</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>:</para>
      <para id="idm512615362224"><m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>X</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo><m:mi>z</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:munderover><m:mo movablelimits="false">∑</m:mo><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:mrow></m:munderover><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:msup><m:mi>z</m:mi><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">X(z)=\sum\limits_{n=-\infty}^{\infty}x[n]z^{-n}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>.</para>
      <para id="idm512614403088">Given that this is an <emphasis effect="italics">infinite</emphasis> sum (unlike, say, the sum of <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>N</m:mi></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">N</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> terms in a DFT), it will not necessarily converge for all <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">x[n]</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> and/or all <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>z</m:mi></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">z</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>. For some <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">x[n]</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>, it will converge for all values of <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>z</m:mi></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">z</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>. For example, if <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mi>δ</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">x[n]=\delta[n]</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>, then:</para>
      <para id="idm512614385472"><m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>X</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo><m:mi>z</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:munderover><m:mo movablelimits="false">∑</m:mo><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:mrow></m:munderover><m:mi>δ</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:msup><m:mi>z</m:mi><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi></m:mrow></m:msup><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">X(z)=\sum\limits_{n=-\infty}^{\infty}\delta[n]z^{-n}=1</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>.</para>
      <para id="idm512614372048">For some <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">x[n]</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>, the sum will not converge for any <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>z</m:mi></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">z</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>. For example, if <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">x[n]=1</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>,  there is no <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>z</m:mi></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">z</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> such that the sum converges.</para>
    </section>
    <section id="idm512614361536">
      <title>The Region of Convergence</title>
      <para id="idm512614360992">So for some <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">x[n]</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> (like <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mi>δ</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">x[n]=\delta[n]</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>) the z-transform sum will converge for <emphasis effect="italics">all </emphasis><m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>z</m:mi></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">z</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>, and for some <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">x[n]</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> (like <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">x[n]=1</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>) the z-transform will not converge for <emphasis effect="italics">any </emphasis><m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>z</m:mi></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">z</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>. As you might suspect, there are some <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">x[n]</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> for which the sum converges for <emphasis effect="italics">some </emphasis><m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>z</m:mi></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">z</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>. These values of <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>z</m:mi></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">z</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>, those for which the z-transform exists, are known as the z-transform's <term><emphasis>region of convergence</emphasis></term>. Consider, for example the z-transform for the signal <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:msup><m:mi>α</m:mi><m:mi>n</m:mi></m:msup><m:mi>u</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mtext> </m:mtext><m:mo>,</m:mo><m:mtext> </m:mtext><m:mi>α</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>.8</m:mn></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">x_1[n]=\alpha^n u[n]~,~\alpha=.8</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>:</para>
      <figure id="idm512614323104"><media id="idm512614322304" alt="">
          <image mime-type="" src="../../media/xRA.png"/>
<image mime-type="application/postscript" src="../../media/xRA.eps" for="pdf"/>
        </media>
        
      </figure><para id="idm512614320560"><m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mtable columnalign="right left right left right left right left right left right left" rowspacing="3pt" columnspacing="0em 2em 0em 2em 0em 2em 0em 2em 0em 2em 0em" displaystyle="true"><m:mtr><m:mtd><m:msub><m:mi>X</m:mi><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo><m:mi>z</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo></m:mtd><m:mtd><m:mi/><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:munderover><m:mo>∑</m:mo><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:mrow></m:munderover><m:msub><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mspace width="thinmathspace"/><m:msup><m:mi>z</m:mi><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mtd></m:mtr><m:mtr><m:mtd/><m:mtd><m:mi/><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:munderover><m:mo>∑</m:mo><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:mrow></m:munderover><m:msup><m:mi>α</m:mi><m:mi>n</m:mi></m:msup><m:mspace width="thinmathspace"/><m:msup><m:mi>z</m:mi><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mtd></m:mtr><m:mtr><m:mtd/><m:mtd><m:mi/><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:munderover><m:mo>∑</m:mo><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:mrow></m:munderover><m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo><m:mi>α</m:mi><m:mspace width="thinmathspace"/><m:msup><m:mi>z</m:mi><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msup><m:msup><m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi></m:msup></m:mtd></m:mtr><m:mtr><m:mtd/><m:mtd><m:mi/><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mrow><m:mo>{</m:mo><m:mtable columnalign="left left" rowspacing=".2em" columnspacing="1em" displaystyle="false"><m:mtr><m:mtd><m:mfrac><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mrow><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi>α</m:mi><m:mspace width="thinmathspace"/><m:msup><m:mi>z</m:mi><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mrow></m:mfrac></m:mtd><m:mtd><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mo stretchy="false">|</m:mo></m:mrow><m:mi>α</m:mi><m:msup><m:mi>z</m:mi><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msup><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mo stretchy="false">|</m:mo></m:mrow><m:mo>&lt;</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mtd></m:mtr><m:mtr><m:mtd><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mtext>undefined</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mtd><m:mtd><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mtext>else</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mtd></m:mtr></m:mtable><m:mo fence="true" stretchy="true"/></m:mrow></m:mtd></m:mtr></m:mtable></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">\begin{align*}
X_1(z) &amp;=\sum_{n=-\infty}^{\infty}  x_1[n] \, z^{-n}\\
&amp;= \sum_{n=0}^{\infty}  \alpha^n \, z^{-n}\\
&amp;= \sum_{n=0}^{\infty}  (\alpha \, z^{-1})^n\\
&amp;=\begin{cases}
\frac{1}{1-\alpha \, z^{-1}}&amp;|\alpha z^{-1}|\lt 1\\
\textrm{undefined}&amp;\textrm{else}
\end{cases}
\end{align*}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>.</para>
      <para id="idm512615341424">So, the z-transform <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>X</m:mi><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo><m:mi>z</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">X_1(z)</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> only exists for <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mo stretchy="false">|</m:mo></m:mrow><m:mi>α</m:mi><m:msup><m:mi>z</m:mi><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msup><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mo stretchy="false">|</m:mo></m:mrow><m:mo>&lt;</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">|\alpha z^{-1}|\lt 1</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>, or put another way, for <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mo stretchy="false">|</m:mo></m:mrow><m:mi>z</m:mi><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mo stretchy="false">|</m:mo></m:mrow><m:mo>&gt;</m:mo><m:mi>α</m:mi></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">|z|\gt \alpha</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>; it is not defined for other values of <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>z</m:mi></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">z</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>. This should not be too terribly shocking, for we are familiar with other functions that only exist for certain values, e.g. <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>log</m:mi><m:mo>⁡</m:mo><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi>x</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">\log{x}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> only for <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo>&gt;</m:mo><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">x\gt 0</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>, or <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mfrac><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mi>x</m:mi></m:mfrac></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">\frac{1}{x}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> only for <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo>≠</m:mo><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">x\neq 0</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>.</para>
      <para id="eip-797">However, there is a difference between the z-transform and its region of convergence and functions like <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>log</m:mi><m:mo>⁡</m:mo><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi>x</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">\log{x}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> or <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mfrac><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mi>x</m:mi></m:mfrac></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">\frac{1}{x}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>. Where the defined regions of existence of the values of <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>log</m:mi><m:mo>⁡</m:mo><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi>x</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">\log{x}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> or <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mfrac><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mi>x</m:mi></m:mfrac></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">\frac{1}{x}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> are quite clear, there is nothing intrinsic about the function <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mfrac><m:mi>z</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mi>z</m:mi><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi>α</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mfrac></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">\frac{z}{z-\alpha}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> to suggest it only exists for <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mo stretchy="false">|</m:mo></m:mrow><m:mi>z</m:mi><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mo stretchy="false">|</m:mo></m:mrow><m:mo>&gt;</m:mo><m:mi>α</m:mi></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">|z|\gt\alpha</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> (of course it is apparent that <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>z</m:mi></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">z</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> cannot equal <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>α</m:mi></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">\alpha</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>). Why in the world would it be a problem if <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>z</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mi>α</m:mi><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mo>/</m:mo></m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">z=\alpha/2</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>, for then we would simply have <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mfrac><m:mrow><m:mi>α</m:mi><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mo>/</m:mo></m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>α</m:mi><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mo>/</m:mo></m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi>α</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mfrac><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">\frac{\alpha/2}{\alpha/2-\alpha}=-1</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>, right? The reason is that the function was the simplification of the <emphasis effect="italics">sum</emphasis>, a simplification that existed only for certain <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>z</m:mi></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">z</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>.</para>
      <para id="eip-852">To see why that is the case, consider another signal related to the one we just considered. Let <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:msup><m:mi>α</m:mi><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mi>n</m:mi></m:mrow></m:msup><m:mi>u</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo><m:mtext> </m:mtext><m:mo>,</m:mo><m:mtext> </m:mtext><m:mi>α</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>.8</m:mn></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">x_2[n]=-\alpha^{n} u[-n-1]~,~\alpha=.8</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>:</para>
