        </m:math>
      </para>
      <para id="eip-570">So for <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">x_2[n]</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>, its z-transform is defined only for <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mo stretchy="false">|</m:mo></m:mrow><m:msup><m:mi>α</m:mi><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msup><m:mi>z</m:mi><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mo stretchy="false">|</m:mo></m:mrow><m:mo>&lt;</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">|\alpha^{-1}z|\lt 1</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>, or equivalently, <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mo stretchy="false">|</m:mo></m:mrow><m:mi>z</m:mi><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mo stretchy="false">|</m:mo></m:mrow><m:mo>&lt;</m:mo><m:mi>α</m:mi></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">|z|\lt\alpha</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>, and for those values it is <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mfrac><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mrow><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi>α</m:mi><m:msup><m:mi>z</m:mi><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mrow></m:mfrac></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">\frac{1}{1-\alpha z^{-1}}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>. Now we see another reason why the region of convergence is so important; it is not merely added information about the z-transform, it is intrinsic to its very definition. The z-transforms for <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">x_1[n]</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> and <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">x_2[n]</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> are completely different, which is to be expected as those are completely different signals. However, the only difference between the transforms is the region of convergence:</para>
      <para id="idm512612190208">
        <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
          <m:semantics>
            <m:mrow>
              <m:mtable columnalign="right left right left right left right left right left right left" rowspacing="3pt" columnspacing="0em 2em 0em 2em 0em 2em 0em 2em 0em 2em 0em" displaystyle="true">
                <m:mtr>
                  <m:mtd>
                    <m:msub>
                      <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                      <m:mn>1</m:mn>
                    </m:msub>
                    <m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo>
                    <m:mi>n</m:mi>
                    <m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo>
                    <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                    <m:msup>
                      <m:mi>α</m:mi>
                      <m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                        <m:mi>n</m:mi>
                      </m:mrow>
                    </m:msup>
                    <m:mi>u</m:mi>
                    <m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo>
                    <m:mi>n</m:mi>
                    <m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo>
                  </m:mtd>
                  <m:mtd>
                    <m:mi/>
                    <m:mo stretchy="false">↔</m:mo>
                    <m:msub>
                      <m:mi>X</m:mi>
                      <m:mn>1</m:mn>
                    </m:msub>
                    <m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo>
                    <m:mi>z</m:mi>
                    <m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo>
                    <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                    <m:mrow>
                      <m:mo>{</m:mo>
                      <m:mtable columnalign="left left" rowspacing=".2em" columnspacing="1em" displaystyle="false">
                        <m:mtr>
                          <m:mtd>
                            <m:mfrac>
                              <m:mn>1</m:mn>
                              <m:mrow>
                                <m:mn>1</m:mn>
                                <m:mo>−</m:mo>
                                <m:mi>α</m:mi>
                                <m:mspace width="thinmathspace"/>
                                <m:msup>
                                  <m:mi>z</m:mi>
                                  <m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                                    <m:mo>−</m:mo>
                                    <m:mn>1</m:mn>
                                  </m:mrow>
                                </m:msup>
                              </m:mrow>
                            </m:mfrac>
                          </m:mtd>
                          <m:mtd>
                            <m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                              <m:mo stretchy="false">|</m:mo>
                            </m:mrow>
                            <m:mi>z</m:mi>
                            <m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                              <m:mo stretchy="false">|</m:mo>
                            </m:mrow>
                            <m:mo>&gt;</m:mo>
                            <m:mi>α</m:mi>
                          </m:mtd>
                        </m:mtr>
                        <m:mtr>
                          <m:mtd>
                            <m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                              <m:mtext>undefined</m:mtext>
                            </m:mrow>
                          </m:mtd>
                          <m:mtd>
                            <m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                              <m:mtext>else</m:mtext>
                            </m:mrow>
                          </m:mtd>
                        </m:mtr>
                      </m:mtable>
                      <m:mo fence="true" stretchy="true"/>
                    </m:mrow>
                  </m:mtd>
                </m:mtr>
                <m:mtr>
                  <m:mtd>
                    <m:msub>
                      <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                      <m:mn>2</m:mn>
                    </m:msub>
                    <m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo>
                    <m:mi>n</m:mi>
                    <m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo>
                    <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                    <m:mo>−</m:mo>
                    <m:msup>
                      <m:mi>α</m:mi>
                      <m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                        <m:mi>n</m:mi>
                      </m:mrow>
                    </m:msup>
                    <m:mi>u</m:mi>
                    <m:mo stretchy="false">[</m:mo>
                    <m:mo>−</m:mo>
                    <m:mi>n</m:mi>
                    <m:mo>−</m:mo>
                    <m:mn>1</m:mn>
                    <m:mo stretchy="false">]</m:mo>
                  </m:mtd>
                  <m:mtd>
                    <m:mi/>
                    <m:mo stretchy="false">↔</m:mo>
                    <m:msub>
                      <m:mi>X</m:mi>
                      <m:mn>2</m:mn>
                    </m:msub>
                    <m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo>
                    <m:mi>z</m:mi>
                    <m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo>
                    <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                    <m:mrow>
                      <m:mo>{</m:mo>
                      <m:mtable columnalign="left left" rowspacing=".2em" columnspacing="1em" displaystyle="false">
                        <m:mtr>
                          <m:mtd>
                            <m:mfrac>
                              <m:mn>1</m:mn>
                              <m:mrow>
                                <m:mn>1</m:mn>
                                <m:mo>−</m:mo>
                                <m:mi>α</m:mi>
                                <m:mspace width="thinmathspace"/>
                                <m:msup>
                                  <m:mi>z</m:mi>
                                  <m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                                    <m:mo>−</m:mo>
                                    <m:mn>1</m:mn>
                                  </m:mrow>
                                </m:msup>
                              </m:mrow>
                            </m:mfrac>
                          </m:mtd>
                          <m:mtd>
                            <m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                              <m:mo stretchy="false">|</m:mo>
                            </m:mrow>
                            <m:mi>z</m:mi>
                            <m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                              <m:mo stretchy="false">|</m:mo>
                            </m:mrow>
                            <m:mo>&lt;</m:mo>
                            <m:mi>α</m:mi>
                          </m:mtd>
                        </m:mtr>
                        <m:mtr>
                          <m:mtd>
                            <m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                              <m:mtext>undefined</m:mtext>
                            </m:mrow>
                          </m:mtd>
                          <m:mtd>
                            <m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                              <m:mtext>else</m:mtext>
                            </m:mrow>
                          </m:mtd>
                        </m:mtr>
                      </m:mtable>
                      <m:mo fence="true" stretchy="true"/>
                    </m:mrow>
                  </m:mtd>
                </m:mtr>
              </m:mtable>
            </m:mrow>
            <m:annotation encoding="math/tex">\begin{align*}
x_1[n]=\alpha^{n} u[n]&amp;\leftrightarrow X_1(z)=\begin{cases}  \frac{1}{1-\alpha \, z^{-1}}&amp;|z|\gt\alpha\\
\textrm{undefined}&amp;\textrm{else}\end{cases}\\
x_2[n]=-\alpha^{n} u[-n-1]&amp;\leftrightarrow X_2(z)=\begin{cases}  \frac{1}{1-\alpha \, z^{-1}}&amp;|z|\lt\alpha\\
\textrm{undefined}&amp;\textrm{else}\end{cases}
\end{align*}</m:annotation>
          </m:semantics>
        </m:math>
      </para>
    </section>
    <section id="idm512612220816">
      <title>Types of ROCs</title>
      <para id="idm512612128736">We have seen a few different types of ROCs for the z-transforms of various signals. If the z-transform for a discrete-time signal exists, then the region of convergence will fall into one of these three categories:</para>
      <list id="idm512612128256" list-type="bulleted">
        <item>If the signal has a finite non-zero duration, then the region of convergence will be the entire z-plane, with the possible exception of <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>z</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">z=\infty</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> (if the signal has nonzero values at time indices less than zero) or <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>z</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">z=0</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> (if the signal has nonzero values at time indices greater than zero).</item>
        <item>If the signal is of infinite duration as <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>n</m:mi></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">n</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> approaches <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">\infty</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> (but not <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">-\infty</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>), then the region of convergence will extend outside some disk (e.g., <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mo stretchy="false">|</m:mo></m:mrow><m:mi>z</m:mi><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mo stretchy="false">|</m:mo></m:mrow><m:mo>&gt;</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">|z|\gt 1</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>) </item>
        <item>If the signal is of infinite duration as <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>n</m:mi></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">n</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> approaches <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">-\infty</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> (but not <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">\infty</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>), then the region of convergence will be inside some disk (e.g., <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mo stretchy="false">|</m:mo></m:mrow><m:mi>z</m:mi><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mo stretchy="false">|</m:mo></m:mrow><m:mo>&lt;</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">|z|\lt 1</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>) </item>
        <item>If the signal is of infinite duration as <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>n</m:mi></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">n</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> approaches both <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">\infty</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> and <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi mathvariant="normal">∞</m:mi></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">-\infty</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>, then the region of convergence--if it exists at all--will be an annulus (e.g., <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mo>&lt;</m:mo><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mo stretchy="false">|</m:mo></m:mrow><m:mi>z</m:mi><m:mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD"><m:mo stretchy="false">|</m:mo></m:mrow><m:mo>&lt;</m:mo><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="math/tex">1\lt |z|\lt 2</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>)
</item>
      </list>
    </section>
